	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=1&mid=106450876138400>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=1&mid=106450876138400>RE: Money And Stuff</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=1&mid=106450876138400#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Sep 25th 1:07 PM 2003</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=172129><span id=Scholar>Azeccia</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>24 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.12]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Head into a dungeon like upperguk or even HHK and farm all the mobs with Fine Steel weapons, loot to full and sell. Another ok way to make some fast pp is to hunt Gremlins in Tenebrous mts, Gorangas in Dawnshroud Peaks, or the like type o'zone for blocks of Acrylia. You may even consider trying to camp the Geonoids in Crystal Caverns for Gem drops or Hill Giants in Rathe mts for great amounts of Coin drops and Fine Steel (not the best place unless it is really empty from other HG hunters or unless you can keep from being KS'ed). <br><br>Last but least, there is always the Bazaar market game. Boring as it may be, it is known to be very profitable. I have made some fast and easy sums of pp when I was willing to blow a couple of weeks or so and actually tried to keep track of prices of what was great buys and a prices not to be missed. <br><br>It is really funny but there are 3 common types of Bazaar players...<br><br>One is the lazy Trader who gets a bunch of gear and sets a price once and leaves these items on their trader for weeks on end without ever even checking if their set price is too high (my favorite type of person since they make my goods at an undercut price sell that much faster). <br><br>Second type of Traders are the type that just want to sell their stuff and be done with it as fast as possible so they can get back to playing their characters, they lack the resources to keep a persistant trader up, or they just have no clue of what a going rate is for their items and are too lazy to find out. This type of person is a hoot since you can get some really great deals off of them and turn around and sell that very same item for a profit and yet still be well below the first type of Trader.<br><br>The third type of Trader is the tricky ones. They are the hunters of deals who actually spend time researching the current prices and has some sort of concept of what items are in demand at the current moment.<br><br>A price on items can fluxuate very rapidly, one day the price being very low then for some mysterious reason it goes back up again. Knowing when is the right time to raise your prices or lower them is the key.<br><br>This third type of person spends a few times a day to raise or drop a going price on their items according to what the supply and demand is at that time or to undercut another Trader by a few hundred pp just to ensure that they are above their price they had bought that item for originally but still the lowest price on the current market. This method ensures that their goods sell first before the rest on the market. <br><br>Think about this...You are the weary adventurer who finally scraped up a few 1000 platinum pieces and are prepared to buy that upgrade youv'e been wanting. <br><br>Now you are not rich therefore you perform a /Bazaar and begin to look for the upgrade and find that there are four currently being sold. One is for an outrageous price of 9k (this is type person number one, the lazy ones who seem to have no clue). The next price is for 3k. Another is for 2.5k. The last one is for 2400pp. Now which one will you rush right out to buy? That's right the one that was the cheapest.<br><br>This is also the tricky part. You do not want to sell too low or you will end up hurting yourself in the long run. If the average price for this item is around 2.5k and you bought it originally for 1.9k and end up lowering it to 2k then, yes you did make a profit but you just lost out on pp aswell since that person who had their's at 2.5k and has been watching the market price like a hawk will just buy yours and resale for the same 2.5k their other one was for. Now they control the two lowest prices and will gaurantee a sale or two before anyone else comes buy to undercut theirs by 100pp or so.<br><br>This is why the last type of person has to spend a lot of time and effort but the return is really worth it in the end.<br><br><br>Vaylain Zek'Bressen - 58 Dark Elven Defiler<br>Merrek Winterstorm - 53 Barbarian Mystic<br>Quintrayle Benevolencia - 51 High Elven Vicar<br>Azeccia Battlebow - 47 Human Ranger<br>Koobek Druidslayer - 43 Ogre Beastlord<br>Vicaria Battlescar - 43 Barbarian Warrior<br>Rhavi S'ythisss - 42 Iksar Monk<br>Zyaden Bladestone - 41 Barbarian Rogue<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Sep 26 09:44:05 2003</em></p>&nbsp;<br></td></td></tr>
